description.text:
This is a simple variation of the reasonably plain S-hooks that snap together. However this one is intended to be glued. Additionally you could glue non-printed things to them, like seashells or whatever tickles your fancy.

This also avoids the stress mark that happens when my tab & socket version were pressed together too tightly. (First picture, I don't have a photo here of the glued one's fronts)

The hook parts come in three different angles, pick one that works for your facing piece.
A is intended to be pretty vertical. C will have the curtain hang off the facing piece the most. B is somewhere in the middle. The curtain is going to hang from the center of where it pulls on the S hook.

You can support me by liking one of my droid pages on YouTube or Facebook :) http://Facebook.com/myL3G0 or http://Facebook.com/LegoBB8.

Printer:

FlashForge

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2mm Medium

Infill:

15% (S hooks)

Notes:

The faces I printed with supports to hold the middle up a bit. The hooks are intended to be printed without support. Mine didn't fit together perfectly cleanly, you may need to clean them a hair, but I just jammed them together and glued them.

You might want to try one of the A, B & C (or at least A & C) versions to see how they hang and if you like that effect. My "real" store bought hangers are similar to the B & C versions, so the curtain gets pressed up against the face and pulls on that. That causes the face to point toward the floor a little. I designed the A hanger so that the face could be vertical and not at an angle.

For my ABS, a drop of superglue was sufficient to connect the two. If you don't want glue, look at the thing this was remixed from, reasonably plain S-hooks

title: Synchromesh Cable Idler Pulley for 608 bearings

description.text: This is an idler pulley for using Synchromesh Cable from SDP/SI ( https://sdp-si.com/eStore/PartDetail.asp?Opener=Group&PartID=84751&GroupID=768 ) in place of belts for linear motion on RepRap style printers. You can see a video of my Prusa printing with these cables here: http://youtu.be/0GMzYMI6rf8 Using this cable and non-printed pulleys gives zero backlash for me and is a nice upgrade from T5 or XL belts. It's also fairly cheap and very lightweight.

Print and insert bearing while still hot. When it cools it will be quite tight. You'll need one for the x-axis and two for the y axis on a standard Prusa. Buy some Synchromesh Cable and pulleys and enjoy better print quality! You'll also need to adjust your steps-per-mm in your firmware. Use the formula: steps per mm = (steps per motor revolution) / (number of teeth * cable pitch) = steps per millimeter For example, I used a 15 tooth pulley ( https://sdp-si.com/eStore/PartDetail.asp?Opener=Group&PartID=5503&GroupID=312 ) and I have 1.8 degree stepper motors with 1/16 microstepping drivers: steps per mm = 3200 / (15 * 3.81) = 55.993 Good luck!

title: Radjet 800 Winglets
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
This are winglets for the famous Radjet 800 from Hobbyking.
The tiptanks are normaly breaking away after a few flights, so this winglets are perfect to improve the look and flyability of your Radjet.

The straight flying is improved and also the stall speed, so with the winglets you can fly slower and with a higher alpha. Also they minimize the ground effect so that the landings also get easier.

Printer:

Prusa i3 Pro X

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0,1

Infill:

10% rectangular

Notes:

I've tested very long to print them good. You should use ABS to not get any heat problems under the sun on the flying field.
Print them with a skirt of 10 lines, starting with a layer height of 0,2mm. Then print with 0,1mm layer height, 10% rectangular infill and 3 outlines.
As printspeed I would recommend 65mm/s until the logo begins, reduce it for that to ~25mm/s (otherwise you will get ringing) and then put it back to 65mm/s.
Set the cooling to slow down under 20 sec. to min. 10mm/s and activate the fan under 10 seconds.

Then they should be printed fine.

If you like, you can try to print them one by one, but i got worse results because of overheating so I'm printing them both together with the downside facing to each other.

If they are made of ABS you can get a real nice glossy finish by using acetone, but however, 0,1mm is already quite fine and you maybe only need some sand paper.

To attach them to the wing:
You need to cut the wing according the meassurements of the pictures, they should be self describing.
I've added to holes per winglet to put a toothpick in it for better stabilisation. Check the attached drawing for the meassurement to find out where to put the toothpicks in the wing. Just glue then the winglets, the wing and the toothpicks with CA glue together.

I've tested them up to 250km/h :)

Info: The logo on them is pAirformance, this is the label under which I'm producing parts and modells for r/c models or also complete r/c models. Check out www.pAirformance.at.vu soon for more information.

The 5mm threaded rods on my P3Steel XL kit were working fine but very squeaky and about as straight as a banana so I decided to upgrade to some 8mm lead screws (300mm length in my case).

Inspired by harari's Prusa i3 lead screw upgrade and using KitPrinter3D's printed parts as a base, I've remixed the 2 to make a drop in replacement for P3Steel Z threaded rods to lead screws.

Harari's upgrade would have required new printed mounts for my Z axis motors and I wanted to keep the solid steel mounts in place.

To get everything to fit snuggly, I had to file about 1.5mm off the side of the brass couplings that came with my 8mm lead screws. The fit for the brass parts is tight enough with my print out that I've not actually screwed it on but there are 3mm holes and space for nuts to match.

Note: I slightly upgraded the linear bearing housing on the parts after taking the pictures.

comments.text: It was just bare aluminum. If you follow that link to the product page, there's Frequently Asked Questions link at the bottom. This will give you some general recommendations on printing. This is a simple UNO card game deck holder consisting of two parts. Design is inspired by JeremyVS's "Customizable Card Box with Cutouts" and been modified to fit the UNO card design.

Notes:

I printed this in PLA on my Afinibot A3 (prusa i3) using Sli3er and Repetier-Host with the following parameters:

  • 2 perimeters
  • 2 solid layers (top/bottom)
  • 15% infill
  • 0.2mm layer hight (first layer 0.3mm)

PLEASE NOTE: You will have to rotate the top cover 180° around the X- or Y-axis to place the flat side on the printer bed.

Compared to the source design I edited some elements like elliptical cutout to fit the design of the UNO card game, so you can see the UNO logo nearly completely. I also rounded the corners of the box, edited the clips and added some structured areas on the sides of the cover for a better grip. At last I splited the Thing into two separat STL-files to print both parts of the box separately.
